00:00:21.636 --> 00:00:24.780
PROFESSOR: We've been talking
so far about basically

00:00:24.780 --> 00:00:27.700
overviews of supply and demand
relationships and

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:30.670
understanding how
markets work.

00:00:30.670 --> 00:00:34.950
Now we're going to step back and
get behind the supply and

00:00:34.950 --> 00:00:38.400
demand curves and understand
where those curves

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.520
themselves come from.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.490
So we talked about, given that
we have supply and demand

00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:43.730
curves, how they interact.

00:00:43.730 --> 00:00:45.650
Now we're going to get behind
that and see where these

00:00:45.650 --> 00:00:47.400
curves actually come from.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:48.550
Thank you, by the way
for coming down.

00:00:48.550 --> 00:00:49.800
I appreciate it.

00:00:51.730 --> 00:00:53.490
So what we're going to do is,
we're going to start with the

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:56.410
demand curve, and we're going to
spend the next few lectures

00:00:56.410 --> 00:00:59.830
talking about consumers and how
consumer preferences are

00:00:59.830 --> 00:01:01.555
ultimately what leads
to the construction

00:01:01.555 --> 00:01:03.380
of the demand curve.

00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:08.200
Then after that and after the
first exam-- that will cover

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:11.250
what's on the first exam--

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:13.740
after the first exam, we'll
start talking about firms and

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:16.380
what determines the
firm supply curve.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:19.210
So today we'll talk about
consumers and we're going to

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:21.580
talk about where the demand
curve comes from.

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:24.810
And where it comes from, and
where all consumer behavior

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:27.665
coming from in economics is
from utility maximization.

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:35.980
That's where everything with
consumers starts is with

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:37.790
utility maximization.

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:44.030
That's the basic building block
of consumer behavior.

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:48.050
And basically, utility
maximization--

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:50.330
that's what this lecture will
be about, describing it.

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:55.410
But basically, an overview
is, we posit some type of

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:56.870
preferences.

00:01:56.870 --> 00:02:03.070
We posit consumer preferences,
what consumers would like.

00:02:03.070 --> 00:02:10.370
We posit some budget constraint,
what resources

00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:12.980
consumers have to get
what they'd like.

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:16.360
And then we do a constrained
maximization problem that

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:20.500
says, given your preferences,
given what you'd like, subject

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:22.840
to the resources you have
available, what

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.870
choices will you make?

00:02:25.870 --> 00:02:27.710
And in particular, we're going
to ask, the term we'll use is

00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:32.860
we'll ask what bundle of goods
makes you the best off?

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:34.020
Given your preference, given
your constraints,

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.510
what bundle of goods?

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:37.050
So think about consumers
choosing

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:38.160
across a set of goods.

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:41.390
Typically, we'll think about two
goods because graphs are

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:43.760
easier to think about two
dimensions than more.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:46.230
So we'll typically think about
trading off two goods.

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:49.140
So think about consumers with
preferences across two goods,

00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:51.880
some budget they can
allocate, and how

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:53.080
they make those choices.

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:56.170
But this basic framework applies
to the multiplicity of

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:59.790
choices we all make along
many, many dimensions.

00:02:59.790 --> 00:03:03.380
So doing two dimensions as one
of the simplifying assumptions

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:04.560
I'll talk about.

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:07.590
But that's just a simplifying
assumption.

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:08.930
So basically what we we're going
to do is we're going to

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:13.180
go through this in three
steps, not just in this

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:15.740
lecture, but over the
next few lectures.

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:19.600
Step one, is we're going to talk
about what assumptions we

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:21.300
make about preferences.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:23.235
So I'll talk today about
preference assumptions.

00:03:27.540 --> 00:03:32.320
So the axioms that underlie how
economists model consumer

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:34.600
preferences.

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.840
We'll then talk about how we
translate these preferences

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:42.770
assumptions into mathematical
tractability through the use

00:03:42.770 --> 00:03:48.570
of the utility function, which
is basically a mathematical

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:52.690
representation of underlying
consumer preferences.

00:03:52.690 --> 00:03:54.660
So we'll talk about how we
basically take these

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:56.560
preferences and translate them
into something that we can

00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.440
work with here at MIT by making
it mathematical, by

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:01.420
making a utility function.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:06.560
And then finally, we'll talk
about budget constraints.

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:09.360
And armed with these three
things, we'll then be able to

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:12.610
model how consumers
make decisions.

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:18.120
Now, importantly for today's
lecture, we are not dealing

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:19.420
with budget constraints.

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:22.690
So this is not happening
today.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:24.280
So today we're not going to
worry about the budget

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:24.530
constraints.

00:04:24.530 --> 00:04:26.325
Today we're in a world where
we're just going to talk about

00:04:26.325 --> 00:04:28.590
what people want and we're going
to put out of our mind

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:31.140
whether or not they
can afford it.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:32.690
So just talk about people want,
and we'll put out of

00:04:32.690 --> 00:04:33.200
mind for today.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.440
We'll come back next time to
whether they can afford it.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:36.910
We're just going to think
about unconstrained

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:39.810
preferences for today's
lecture.

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:47.310
So let's talk about our
preference assumptions.

00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:53.180
So, to model consumers'
preferences across goods,

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:55.360
we're going to impose three
preference assumptions.

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:05.160
Three preference assumptions.

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:06.260
Assumption one--

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:08.990
now once again, let me remind
you from the first lecture,

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:11.260
this is getting to some of
the harder material.

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:15.320
I'm going to write messily and
talk quickly, so stop me if

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:16.520
anything is unclear.

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:18.450
And if you don't stop me, I'll
just go faster and faster

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:19.860
until I explode.

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:22.190
So basically, feel free to
interrupt and stop me with

00:05:22.190 --> 00:05:24.260
questions and such.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:26.400
Three assumptions
on preferences.

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:27.800
The first assumption
is completeness.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.140
The first assumption is the
assumption of completeness.

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:38.910
When comparing two bundles of
goods, you prefer one or the

00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:44.180
other, but you don't
value them equally.

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:46.720
OK when comparing two bundles
of goods, you prefer one or

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:48.870
you prefer the other, but
you're not indifferent.

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:51.860
Completeness is the same
as no indifference.

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:54.230
So what we're saying is whenever
I offer you two

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:56.170
bundles of goods, you
could always tell me

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:57.090
what you like better.

00:05:57.090 --> 00:05:59.490
Now it could be infinitesimally
better.

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:01.440
I'm not saying you have to
have strong preferences.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:04.330
But you cannot say
I'm indifferent.

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:05.680
You can never be purely
indifferent.

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:09.390
There always at least some
slight preference for one

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:11.090
bundle of goods over another.

00:06:11.090 --> 00:06:13.340
That's the completeness
assumption.

00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:14.800
This is an assumption we make.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:17.640
Now in reality, oftentimes
we are indifferent.

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:18.900
Well once again, this is one
of these simplifying

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:20.650
assumptions that will
make the model work.

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:23.200
And in fact, in reality if
forced, you can always decide

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:24.910
whether you like one thing
better than another, we just

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:27.440
often follow heuristic rules
which say we're roughly

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:28.250
indifferent.

00:06:28.250 --> 00:06:29.640
We're just going to say, more
precisely, you are never

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:32.300
purely indifferent.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:35.100
So, I'm not sure is
not an option.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:36.900
You can never say I don't know,
I don't know which I

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.470
prefer, I'm indifferent.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:40.450
I'm sorry, let me back up.

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:41.780
I'm using the wrong word.

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:43.416
Forget I said indifferent,
because we'll want to use that

00:06:43.416 --> 00:06:44.690
word in a different
context later.

00:06:44.690 --> 00:06:47.470
You can't say, I'm not sure.

00:06:47.470 --> 00:06:49.010
You can't say, I'm not sure.

00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:54.580
You can't say, I'm not sure,
can't say I don't know, I

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:55.830
don't know how I feel
about that.

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:05.250
Scratch what I said a few
minutes ago, because I want to

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:06.460
use indifference differently.

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:08.810
Completeness is not about not
being different, we're going

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:09.490
to use that.

00:07:09.490 --> 00:07:11.510
What I'm saying is it's
about not being sure.

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:14.480
You've got to value every
bundle of goods.

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:16.720
You've got to be willing to
value every bundle of goods

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:18.610
that's given you.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:20.500
So you can't say that I don't
know, I don't know how I feel

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:21.110
about that.

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:22.570
You've got to have some
feeling about stuff.

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:23.880
You can't say I'm not sure.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:25.810
You've got to have a complete
set of preferences over all

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:28.680
bundles of goods that
are given you.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:31.910
OK, that's completeness.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:33.640
The second is transitivity.

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:39.930
Which is something we've been
learning since kindergarten

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:41.000
about transitivity, right?

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.570
And also, it's a different
context.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:45.020
That's just if you prefer x to
y, and y to z, you've got to

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:46.140
prefer x to z.

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:47.650
OK, you guys should
do transitivity in

00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:49.010
your sleep by now.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:50.970
OK, so the standard transitivity
we always assume

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:53.870
in math class, we're going
to assume here as well.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:56.800
OK, that should be pretty
noncontroversial.

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:01.400
OK, and then finally, and
probably most controversial,

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:02.990
is we're going to assume
non-satiation.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:09.520
Or the famous economic
assumption that

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:12.120
more is always better.

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:13.260
OK.

00:08:13.260 --> 00:08:17.400
More is always better, that is,
you never would turn down

00:08:17.400 --> 00:08:19.000
having more.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.950
Now we're going to talk later
today and tomorrow about why

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:24.490
you might not like the next unit
as much as you like the

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:25.530
current unit.

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:28.270
But you'll always like
it greater than zero.

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:30.640
You're always happy
to have more.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:32.799
You never say, I've had enough,
I literally value at

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:34.230
zero the next unit.

00:08:34.230 --> 00:08:37.070
You may value it as epsilon, but
you'll always value it as

00:08:37.070 --> 00:08:38.289
greater than zero.

00:08:38.289 --> 00:08:40.130
That's the non-satiation
assumption,

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:41.230
more is always better.

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:42.259
Now, this is the most
controversial.

00:08:42.259 --> 00:08:43.840
And obviously we can think
of many contexts in

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:45.750
which that's not true.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:49.170
But if we don't allow for this
assumption, the modeling gets

00:08:49.170 --> 00:08:50.120
a lot trickier.

00:08:50.120 --> 00:08:51.350
So once again, let's put
it out of our mind.

00:08:51.350 --> 00:08:54.910
Realistically, we know once
we've eaten a certain amount,

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:57.060
we literally do not
want any more.

00:08:57.060 --> 00:08:58.680
OK, so we're going to
put that aside.

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:00.480
Assume we're always in a space
where we can always eat a

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.240
little bit more.

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:04.540
OK, we'll call it the
Jewish mother space.

00:09:04.540 --> 00:09:06.670
OK, you can always eat
a little bit more.

00:09:06.670 --> 00:09:08.430
OK, you can always eat
a little bit more.

00:09:08.430 --> 00:09:10.620
We're just going to assume we're
in that space for now.

00:09:10.620 --> 00:09:11.220
OK.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.360
And so, for large ranges,
we can see it is not an

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:14.170
unreasonable assumption.

00:09:14.170 --> 00:09:15.800
Although, I think in extremes,
you could see this becomes

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:17.320
unreasonable.

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:19.090
OK, so those are assumptions.

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:20.520
Completeness, which once
again, I screwed up in

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:21.360
describing.

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:22.900
Come back to the second way I
described it, which means you

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:23.740
can't say you're not sure.

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:25.970
You always have preferences
over things.

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:27.390
That doesn't seem
unreasonable.

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:29.360
Transitivity which we've been
living with since we were

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:30.070
kindergartners.

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:32.410
And non-satiation, which could
be a little controversial, but

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:33.820
we'll live with it for now.

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:37.570
Now given these, we're going to
talk about the properties

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:39.820
of what we call indifference
curves.

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:41.450
This is why I screwed
up before.

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:43.080
Of course you can be indifferent
between things.

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:43.990
That's the whole point
of economics.

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:47.706
I don't know why I
got that wrong.

00:09:47.706 --> 00:09:50.160
I haven't taught this course
about six years, so I lost

00:09:50.160 --> 00:09:52.130
track of things.

00:09:52.130 --> 00:09:54.170
Properties of indifference
curves.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:59.080
So indifference curves are our
name for what you could also

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:02.325
think of as preference maps.

00:10:02.325 --> 00:10:05.160
In economics, we like to be able
to describe everything,

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:07.600
as I said, three ways,
intuitively, graphically, and

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:08.590
mathematically.

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:12.320
Preference maps are the
graphical representation of

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:14.950
people's preferences which we
do through graphics that we

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:17.130
call indifference curves.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:19.421
So now let's go to the example
I'm going to use that I'm

00:10:19.421 --> 00:10:21.680
going to use throughout these
next couple lectures of a

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:23.470
decision you have to make.

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:26.330
Now I tried to think of a cool
way to make this example cool,

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:26.920
and I just couldn't.

00:10:26.920 --> 00:10:28.630
So its going to be
a boring example.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:31.400
It's going to be, imagine your
parents gave you some money

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:34.760
and you had to decide whether
to buy pizza or see movies.

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:36.340
I tried to make it at least a
little bit relevant even if I

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:37.760
couldn't make it cool.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:39.950
You've got to decide whether
to buy pizza or see movies.

00:10:39.950 --> 00:10:41.110
That's your decision.

00:10:41.110 --> 00:10:42.570
That's the trade-off
you're making.

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:47.150
We're in a world with only two
goods, pizza and movies.

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:49.930
And you're deciding how to
allocate the money your

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:52.210
parents gave you over
pizza and movies.

00:10:56.450 --> 00:10:59.410
Now let's say we're going to
consider three choices of

00:10:59.410 --> 00:11:00.490
pizza and movies.

00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:01.740
So go to figure 4-1a.

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:10.140
We're going to consider, you
could have two pizzas and one

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:15.530
movie, that's point A. You could
have one pizza and two

00:11:15.530 --> 00:11:18.030
movies, that's point B. Or you
can have two of both, that's

00:11:18.030 --> 00:11:21.500
point C. That's just three
choices you're facing.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:23.140
Once again, we're ignoring
paying for them.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:24.860
Budget constraints
is next time.

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:26.950
Now we're just saying I'm giving
these three choices.

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:29.210
Well how do you feel
about them?

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:32.010
Well let's assume that
you're indifferent--

00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:32.970
and this is why you can
be indifferent.

00:11:32.970 --> 00:11:35.070
What I said before,
just strike.

00:11:35.070 --> 00:11:37.000
Let's say you're indifferent
between two pizzas and one

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.150
movie, and one pizza
and two movies.

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:43.730
Let's say, if you had two pizzas
and one movie, or one

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:45.350
pizza and two movies, you pretty
much feel the same

00:11:45.350 --> 00:11:46.360
about them.

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:50.880
But clearly you like two pizzas
and two movies better

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:54.200
than either of the first
two combinations.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.000
Then what we can do is we
can draw what we call

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:58.510
indifference curves.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:01.820
And that's in figure 4-1b.

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:04.330
These are maps of your
preferences.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:09.060
An indifference curve is the
curve showing all combinations

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:13.050
of consumption along which the
individual is indifferent.

00:12:13.050 --> 00:12:14.600
And I'll say that again,
very important concept.

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:17.970
An indifference curve is a curve
showing all combinations

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:22.490
of consumption along which an
individual is indifferent.

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:23.800
So you have an indifference
curve.

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:26.810
I said you were indifferent
between A and B. So you have

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:30.370
an indifference curve that runs
between A and B. That

00:12:30.370 --> 00:12:33.400
means that all, and I'm assuming
that all combinations

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:35.670
along this curve, you're
indifferent.

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:37.850
So you're equally happy getting
two pizzas and one

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:39.820
movie or one pizza
and two movies.

00:12:39.820 --> 00:12:44.566
But point C, which is two pizzas
and two movies is on a

00:12:44.566 --> 00:12:45.530
different indifference curve.

00:12:45.530 --> 00:12:50.120
You're not indifferent between
point C and points A and B.

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:51.340
You're indifferent
between A and B--

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:53.210
I'm just assuming this, I'm
not saying you are.

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:56.050
But I'm just assuming, let's
imagine you are.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:13:01.010
But you clearly like two pizzas
and two movies better

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:03.430
than one of one and
two of the other.

00:13:03.430 --> 00:13:03.927
Yeah?

00:13:03.927 --> 00:13:07.406
AUDIENCE: Does that break the
completeness rule for the--

00:13:07.406 --> 00:13:09.160
PROFESSOR: Does that break it?

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:10.120
Why would that break it?

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:11.411
AUDIENCE: Do you prefer
pizza over movies

00:13:11.411 --> 00:13:12.470
or movies over pizza?

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:13.460
PROFESSOR: No.

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:14.740
Because this is my
screw up before.

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:16.600
Completeness just means you
know how you feel about

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:18.090
everything.

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:22.110
So strike from the record
my initial description.

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:24.030
Completeness means you just
know how you feel about

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:24.620
everything.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:25.960
You're allowed to
be indifferent.

00:13:25.960 --> 00:13:27.416
Completeness just means you
can't say, I don't know, I

00:13:27.416 --> 00:13:28.690
don't know how I feel
about pizza.

00:13:28.690 --> 00:13:30.740
You've got to have feelings
for pizza.

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:31.260
OK.

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:32.490
You've got to know how
you feel about stuff.

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:35.750
That's what completeness is.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:40.780
So armed with those assumptions,
there are four

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:43.530
key properties of indifference
curves that we have

00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:44.700
to keep track of.

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:48.010
Four key properties of
indifference curves.

00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:51.770
The first is that consumers
prefer higher

00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:53.440
indifference curves.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:58.410
So you prefer higher
indifference curves.

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:03.620
Prefer higher indifference
curves.

00:14:03.620 --> 00:14:05.290
What I mean by that is, the
further out the indifference

00:14:05.290 --> 00:14:06.920
curve, the more you prefer it.

00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:11.060
And this comes naturally from
the non-satiation assumption.

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:14.340
Given that we've assumed
non-satiation, you must always

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:16.690
prefer an indifference curve
that's further from the origin

00:14:16.690 --> 00:14:19.770
because it's more, and
more is better.

00:14:19.770 --> 00:14:22.960
OK so given non-satiation,
you will always prefer an

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:26.100
indifference curves that are
further from the origin.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:29.000
That follows directly
from non-satiation.

00:14:31.610 --> 00:14:39.750
The second point is that
indifference curves are always

00:14:39.750 --> 00:14:41.000
downward sloping.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:47.705
Indifference curves are always
downward sloping.

00:14:51.994 --> 00:14:54.050
Indifference curves are always
downward sloping.

00:14:54.050 --> 00:14:56.160
And that, once again, comes
from non-satiation.

00:14:56.160 --> 00:14:59.040
To see this, let's look at the
next figure, an upward sloping

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:02.020
indifference curve.

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:04.320
Why does an upward sloping
indifference curve, someone

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:07.529
tell me, violate
non-satiation.

00:15:07.529 --> 00:15:08.002
Yeah?

00:15:08.002 --> 00:15:10.367
AUDIENCE: Because you're
indifferent to getting more.

00:15:10.367 --> 00:15:10.681
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:15:10.681 --> 00:15:11.850
Because this would say
you're indifferent

00:15:11.850 --> 00:15:13.480
between (1,1) and (2,2).

00:15:13.480 --> 00:15:14.770
It's not quite drawn right.

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:18.010
We ought to just have this go
through to point (2,2).

00:15:18.010 --> 00:15:20.710
But basically, this would say
you're indifferent between

00:15:20.710 --> 00:15:22.610
getting one pizza and
one movie or two

00:15:22.610 --> 00:15:23.870
pizzas and two movies.

00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:26.880
You can't be because that
violates more is better.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.710
So indifference curves can't be
upward sloping, they've got

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:33.510
to be downward sloping by the
non-satiation assumption.

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:37.890
OK, that's the second property
of indifference curves.

00:15:37.890 --> 00:15:40.730
The third property of
indifference curves is

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:42.530
indifference curves
cannot cross.

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:50.080
Indifference curves
cannot cross.

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:51.910
Why can't indifference
curves cross?

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:54.405
Well here I forgot to have
Jessica do a pretty diagram,

00:15:54.405 --> 00:15:57.840
so you'll have to deal with
my ugly handwriting here.

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:00.720
So why can't indifferent
curves cross?

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:03.820
Well imagine a situation
where you have your

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:06.230
pizza and your movies.

00:16:06.230 --> 00:16:11.690
And imagine a situation where
you have one indifference

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:14.150
curve that looks like this,
and one indifference curve

00:16:14.150 --> 00:16:15.840
that looks like this.

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:17.480
OK, two indifference curves.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:25.570
And you've got, let's label
these points A, B, and C.

00:16:25.570 --> 00:16:28.810
Now could someone give me, based
on the properties of

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:31.405
indifference curves that we
talked about over here, given

00:16:31.405 --> 00:16:33.030
these three properties,
can someone tell me

00:16:33.030 --> 00:16:35.440
why this is a violation?

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:35.845
Yeah?

00:16:35.845 --> 00:16:38.628
AUDIENCE: Because A and B are
on the same curve, meaning

00:16:38.628 --> 00:16:41.405
you're indifferent between A and
B. A and C are also on the

00:16:41.405 --> 00:16:43.990
same curve because you're
indifferent between the two.

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:46.693
But that means you're also
indifferent between B and C

00:16:46.693 --> 00:16:48.426
which can't be true because
more is better.

00:16:48.426 --> 00:16:49.490
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:16:49.490 --> 00:16:52.050
So transitivity says I must then
be indifferent between B

00:16:52.050 --> 00:16:54.200
and C through the logic
you just laid out.

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:56.090
But I can't be indifferent
between B and C because B

00:16:56.090 --> 00:17:00.390
dominates C. B has a basically
the same number of movies, but

00:17:00.390 --> 00:17:03.040
more pizza, so I must
like B better.

00:17:03.040 --> 00:17:06.810
So by the combination of
transitivity and non-satiation

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:09.930
indifference curves
can't cross.

00:17:09.930 --> 00:17:13.269
And finally, completeness, which
is the most awkward of

00:17:13.269 --> 00:17:15.770
these assumptions, it simply
means you can't have more than

00:17:15.770 --> 00:17:18.930
one indifference curve
through a point.

00:17:18.930 --> 00:17:24.790
So basically, the idea of every
possible bundle has one

00:17:24.790 --> 00:17:25.730
indifference curve.

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:27.399
You can't have two indifference
curves through it

00:17:27.399 --> 00:17:29.250
sayin, I'm not sure which
indifference curve I'm on.

00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:30.650
I'm not sure how I
feel about this.

00:17:30.650 --> 00:17:31.560
You know how you feel.

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:34.120
There's one indifference curve
through every bundle.

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:37.150
There's not two indifference
curves through a bundle.

00:17:37.150 --> 00:17:40.800
So this is the way we think
about preference maps which is

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:44.350
the sort of core building
block of utility theory.

00:17:44.350 --> 00:17:48.960
Now I was an undergrad here,
took this course, but I never

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:51.820
really understood indifference
curves until I had a year off

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:54.900
with a grad student who was
trying to decide where to take

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:57.672
a job and he did it through
just showing me an

00:17:57.672 --> 00:17:58.900
indifference map.

00:17:58.900 --> 00:18:00.680
He said look, I'm trying to
decide where to take a job,

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:01.600
and I care about two things.

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:04.730
I care about how good the place
is and where it is.

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:09.230
So he said here, he had
location and he

00:18:09.230 --> 00:18:10.870
had academic rank.

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:21.060
And he said look, I'm
indifferent between Princeton

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:26.130
which has a shitty location but
a wonderful academic rank.

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:28.680
I'm from New Jersey, but it's
still a shitty location.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:32.240
OK, and Santa Cruz.

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:37.130
And Santa Cruz which has not
such a good academic

00:18:37.130 --> 00:18:39.250
reputation, but a pretty
awesome location.

00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:42.680
And he said here's my
indifference map.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:43.810
And where did he end up going?

00:18:43.810 --> 00:18:47.730
He ended up going to the IMF,
the international monetary

00:18:47.730 --> 00:18:51.970
fund in DC which had a better
location than Princeton--

00:18:51.970 --> 00:18:54.075
worse than Santa Cruz, but a
better reputation than Santa

00:18:54.075 --> 00:18:55.640
Cruz and worse than Princeton.

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:57.710
So he decided he was indifferent
along this map,

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:00.180
and he ended up choosing
a point in the middle.

00:19:00.180 --> 00:19:02.700
But indifference curves are just
a way of representing two

00:19:02.700 --> 00:19:05.090
dimensional choices.

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:07.110
Now very few choice in life are
really two dimensional,

00:19:07.110 --> 00:19:08.100
but that's a nice example.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:08.865
Question in the back?

00:19:08.865 --> 00:19:12.590
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
IMF, the point would be

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:14.825
actually not on the curve,
but further out?

00:19:14.825 --> 00:19:15.719
PROFESSOR: If it were
further out.

00:19:15.719 --> 00:19:17.225
A great question.

00:19:17.225 --> 00:19:18.740
So imagine if IMF were here.

00:19:21.490 --> 00:19:24.054
What should he have done?

00:19:24.054 --> 00:19:25.380
Definitely go to IMF.

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:26.700
Here he was indifferent.

00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:29.560
He could flip a coin and be
equally happy at all three.

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:31.610
But if IMF were out here, and
maybe it was because that's

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:32.520
what he chose.

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:33.120
That's a good point.

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:36.440
I don't know if IMF
was here or here.

00:19:36.440 --> 00:19:39.380
The fact that he chose
IMF, it can reveal it

00:19:39.380 --> 00:19:40.390
wasn't anywhere in here.

00:19:40.390 --> 00:19:41.760
It's a very good
point actually.

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:44.510
It can reveal it wasn't
anywhere in here.

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:45.510
That we know.

00:19:45.510 --> 00:19:47.420
But I can't tell if it
was on the curve

00:19:47.420 --> 00:19:49.030
or outside the curve.

00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:49.890
It could have been on the
curve because he's

00:19:49.890 --> 00:19:51.720
indifferent, so who knows, he
could have flipped the coin.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:53.470
Or it could have been outside
the curve because it's better.

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:54.360
We can't tell that.

00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:56.220
That's a good point.

00:19:56.220 --> 00:19:57.110
All right.

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:58.590
So that's a preference map.

00:19:58.590 --> 00:20:00.950
That's indifference curves.

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:03.890
Now let's step from indifference
curves, which is

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:07.935
a building block of preferences,
to utility.

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:15.180
Now everything you need to
know about preferences is

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:17.920
represented in those
indifference maps.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:21.630
The problem is they're pretty
awkward to work with when we

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:25.990
need to actually prove theorems
and solve and

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:27.880
understand how people
make decisions.

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:31.060
That's a lot easier if we have
a mathematical representation

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:32.540
of those preference maps.

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:35.280
And that's the utility
function

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:40.200
So the utility function is a
mathematical representation of

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:40.770
preferences.

00:20:40.770 --> 00:20:41.950
That's all it is.

00:20:41.950 --> 00:20:45.415
You're going to be hearing this
term in your nightmares

00:20:45.415 --> 00:20:46.910
for the next semester.

00:20:46.910 --> 00:20:48.060
Utility functions.

00:20:48.060 --> 00:20:51.520
But remember, it's just a
mathematical representation of

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:52.950
people's underlying
preferences.

00:20:52.950 --> 00:20:55.890
Don't be scared of it.

00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:58.450
And the key thing is that we
assume individuals have these

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:01.820
well-defined utility functions,
and by maximizing

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:03.840
those utility functions we can
tell what choices they're

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:05.060
going to make.

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:09.120
So for example, suppose that
I said that your utility

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:13.660
function over pizza and movies
was the square root of pizza

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:16.390
times movies.

00:21:16.390 --> 00:21:17.360
That's a utility function.

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:18.270
I'm going to say, what the
hell does that mean?

00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:19.570
Well, it doesn't mean anything,

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:20.820
it's a utility function.

00:21:20.820 --> 00:21:21.900
It's your preferences.

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:23.280
It's a mathematical
representation of your

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:24.530
preferences.

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:27.730
What does that mean?

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:29.440
What it means is--

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:32.290
it doesn't mean anything
inherently, but it tells us

00:21:32.290 --> 00:21:33.960
about your preferences.

00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:36.880
What it tells us is that
your preferences can be

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:38.450
represented.

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:43.030
If you flip back to figure 4-1b,
it tells us those are

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:47.350
your preferences because you're
indifferent between two

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:50.390
pizzas and one movie and one
pizza and two movies.

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:50.890
Of course you're indifferent.

00:21:50.890 --> 00:21:53.860
They both give a utility
square root two.

00:21:53.860 --> 00:21:56.265
But you prefer two pizzas and
two movies because that gives

00:21:56.265 --> 00:21:58.140
a utility of two.

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:00.650
So this is a mathematical
representation consistent with

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:02.110
those utility indifference
curves.

00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:03.540
Not the only one.

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:04.910
There's other mathematical
representations that could be

00:22:04.910 --> 00:22:06.750
consistent with those
indifference curves.

00:22:06.750 --> 00:22:09.760
But let's posit that this is
your utility function.

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:13.260
This is a mathematical
representation of your tastes.

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:15.120
Now what does utility mean?

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:20.040
Utility means nothing in the
sense that it is not a

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:21.035
cardinal concept.

00:22:21.035 --> 00:22:23.690
It's only an ordinal concept.

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:30.110
So if I say to you that you get
two utils from two pizzas

00:22:30.110 --> 00:22:32.290
and two movies, that doesn't
mean anything.

00:22:32.290 --> 00:22:35.450
It just means that you get
more than from one

00:22:35.450 --> 00:22:36.420
pizza and one movie.

00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:39.080
And we can even get the ratio
that you get square root of

00:22:39.080 --> 00:22:43.320
two more, than you get from
one pizza and two movies.

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:46.340
We can do ranking and
ordinality, but we can't

00:22:46.340 --> 00:22:47.560
assign cardinality.

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:52.260
I can't say how happy you are
in some abstract absolute

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:54.120
sense from two pizzas
and one movie.

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:56.270
I can't give a cardinal
form preference.

00:22:56.270 --> 00:22:58.150
But this is an ordinal ranking
of preferences.

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:01.130
I can tell what you like
better than what else.

00:23:01.130 --> 00:23:03.192
That's why utility function
is a representation of

00:23:03.192 --> 00:23:04.400
indifference maps.

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:07.340
They're just a mathematical tool
for comparing bundles,

00:23:07.340 --> 00:23:09.710
they're not some inner answer
to the value of your soul or

00:23:09.710 --> 00:23:11.250
something like that.

00:23:11.250 --> 00:23:12.660
Don't imbue these with
too much magic.

00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:15.050
They're just mathematical ways
of representing preferences.

00:23:18.110 --> 00:23:22.530
The key concept, the single most
important concept, for

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:25.170
consumer theory for
understanding how consumers

00:23:25.170 --> 00:23:28.245
make decisions is the concept
of marginal utility.

00:23:32.690 --> 00:23:35.150
We'll talk a lot this semester
about marginal this and

00:23:35.150 --> 00:23:36.560
marginal that.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:38.220
And this is our first example.

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:40.840
Marginal utility.

00:23:40.840 --> 00:23:45.740
That is how your utility changes
with each additional

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:47.390
unit of the good, or
the derivative

00:23:47.390 --> 00:23:49.150
of the utility function.

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:51.025
If you want to do it in calculus
terms, marginal

