00:36:54.870 --> 00:36:55.690
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:37:00.010
The MRS is diminishing.

00:37:00.010 --> 00:37:02.180
Technically when you go to grad
school, you realize that

00:37:02.180 --> 00:37:04.020
marginal utility isn't actually
technically always

00:37:04.020 --> 00:37:04.440
diminishing.

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:05.010
I said it is.

00:37:05.010 --> 00:37:06.210
For this course it is.

00:37:06.210 --> 00:37:09.400
But if you want to get
mathematically correct, really

00:37:09.400 --> 00:37:11.550
what's always diminishing that
you prove is the marginal rate

00:37:11.550 --> 00:37:14.670
of substitution is always
diminishing.

00:37:14.670 --> 00:37:16.230
So we have diminishing marginal
utility for the

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:19.490
purpose of this course, but the
really important concept

00:37:19.490 --> 00:37:23.320
is you have diminishing marginal
rate of substitution.

00:37:23.320 --> 00:37:26.140
The rate at which you're willing
to trade off pizza for

00:37:26.140 --> 00:37:31.030
movies is going to fall
as you have less

00:37:31.030 --> 00:37:34.700
pizza and more movies.

00:37:34.700 --> 00:37:37.940
So to see that, look at this
graph, and let's compute the

00:37:37.940 --> 00:37:41.060
marginal rate of substitution
along each segment.

00:37:41.060 --> 00:37:42.050
So let's localize.

00:37:42.050 --> 00:37:44.170
Imagine the segments were
linear, imagine we had two

00:37:44.170 --> 00:37:45.170
linear segments between
these points.

00:37:45.170 --> 00:37:46.000
We don't.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.210
But imagine for a
second we did.

00:37:48.210 --> 00:37:50.970
So the marginal rate of
substitution from the first

00:37:50.970 --> 00:37:55.140
point, four pizzas and one
movie, to the second point,

00:37:55.140 --> 00:37:57.940
two pizzas and two movies,
the marginal rate of

00:37:57.940 --> 00:38:00.570
substitution is -2.

00:38:00.570 --> 00:38:06.380
You are willing to give up two
pizzas to get one movie.

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:08.980
This is the same graph,
figure 4-6.

00:38:08.980 --> 00:38:11.160
This isn't on the graph, you
have to write it on.

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:13.300
So going from that first point
to that second point, you're

00:38:13.300 --> 00:38:18.310
willing to give up two pizzas
to get one movie.

00:38:18.310 --> 00:38:21.330
So that rate of marginal
substitution is -2.

00:38:21.330 --> 00:38:25.620
However, when you're at two
movies and two pizzas, and I

00:38:25.620 --> 00:38:29.220
say OK, how about giving up one
more pizza to see movies?

00:38:29.220 --> 00:38:30.580
Now you say, wait a second.

00:38:30.580 --> 00:38:34.420
To give up one more pizza,
I need to see two movies.

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.390
My marginal rate of substitution
on that second

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:39.340
segment is -1/2.

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:40.680
The marginal rate of
substitution on the first

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:41.990
segment is -2.

00:38:41.990 --> 00:38:43.940
The marginal rate of
substitution on the second

00:38:43.940 --> 00:38:44.690
segment is -1/2.

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:46.860
Once again, assuming they're not
linear, so it's actually

00:38:46.860 --> 00:38:48.587
changing everywhere, but if they
were linear, that's what

00:38:48.587 --> 00:38:49.480
it would be.

00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:51.610
Can someone tell me why?

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:55.230
Why is the marginal rate of
substitution falling?

00:38:55.230 --> 00:38:58.060
Why is the marginal rate of
substitution lower on that

00:38:58.060 --> 00:38:59.959
second segment than
on the first?

00:38:59.959 --> 00:39:04.699
AUDIENCE: Because marginal
utility increases the fewer of

00:39:04.699 --> 00:39:06.446
something you have.

00:39:06.446 --> 00:39:07.950
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:11.180
So go ahead, flesh it out, the
fewer of somthing you have, so

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:13.100
tell me in terms of the trade
you're willing to make.

00:39:13.100 --> 00:39:17.315
AUDIENCE: You value it more, so
you want to trade more of

00:39:17.315 --> 00:39:18.205
something else for it.

00:39:18.205 --> 00:39:22.893
PROFESSOR: The point is when I
have four pizzas my marginal

00:39:22.893 --> 00:39:26.600
utility of that last pizza
is not very high.

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:30.380
And I'm fine to give
up two pizzas--

00:39:30.380 --> 00:39:32.360
and plus I'm only seeing one
movie, there's a second movie

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:33.820
I really want to see.

00:39:33.820 --> 00:39:36.220
So you say to me, look,
I've got four pizzas,

00:39:36.220 --> 00:39:37.700
I'm seeing one movie.

00:39:37.700 --> 00:39:39.420
You say hey, there's a
second movie out I

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:40.460
know you want to see.

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:42.500
I know you don't really
value four pizzas.

00:39:42.500 --> 00:39:43.850
At the end, you're
totally full.

00:39:43.850 --> 00:39:45.350
Would you be willing to give
up two pizzas to see the

00:39:45.350 --> 00:39:45.720
second movie?

00:39:45.720 --> 00:39:47.380
And you're like, sure why not?

00:39:47.380 --> 00:39:50.210
Well once you have two pizzas
and you've seen two movies,

00:39:50.210 --> 00:39:51.930
you're not that interested in
a third movie and you'll be

00:39:51.930 --> 00:39:54.610
hungry if you have less than two
pizzas, so then you say,

00:39:54.610 --> 00:39:55.060
wait a second.

00:39:55.060 --> 00:39:56.970
If you want me to give up
another pizza, you've got to

00:39:56.970 --> 00:39:59.800
give me two movies.

00:39:59.800 --> 00:40:04.220
Because my marginal utility of
pizzas is rising, my marginal

00:40:04.220 --> 00:40:07.570
utility of movies is falling.

00:40:07.570 --> 00:40:09.600
And that's why the marginal
rate of substitution

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:15.490
diminishes along the
indifference curve.

00:40:15.490 --> 00:40:18.160
So that allows us to write
mathematically the definition

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:23.470
of the marginal rate of
substitution is the negative

00:40:23.470 --> 00:40:26.180
of the marginal utility of
movies, or more generally

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:32.030
what's on the x-axis, over the
marginal utility of pizza, or

00:40:32.030 --> 00:40:33.280
more generally what's
on the y-axis.

00:40:35.980 --> 00:40:37.670
The marginal rate of
substitution, the first key

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:39.992
formula you need to know for
this course, the marginal rate

00:40:39.992 --> 00:40:41.060
of substitution is equal to the

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:42.310
ratio of marginal utilities.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:46.720
Now this is tricky.

00:40:49.660 --> 00:40:51.060
Maybe you guys don't find it
tricky, it's the kind of thing

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:52.010
I find tricky.

